In July 2006, as ''Casino Royale'' entered post-production, [[EON Productions]] announced that the next film would be based on an original idea by producer [[Michael G. Wilson]].<ref>{{cite news |author= Tatiana Siegel and Borys Kit |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002840141|title= Roger Michell in Talks for Bond 22 |work= [[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date= 2006-07-17 |accessdate=2006-07-17}}</ref> It was decided beforehand the film would be a direct sequel, to exploit Bond's emotions following Vesper's death in the previous film.<ref>{{cite news | author = Liane Bonin | title = 10 Questions With: Daniel Craig | work = [[Moviefone]] | url = http://www.moviefone.com/insidemovies/2008/04/14/daniel-craig-interview-for-quantum-of-solace/ | accessdate=2008-04-11}}</ref> Just as ''Casino Royale'''s theme was [[terrorism]], the sequel focuses on [[environmentalism]].<ref name=environment/> The film was confirmed for a 2 May 2008 release date, with Craig reprising the lead role.<ref>{{cite news |author=[[Columbia Pictures]] |title=22nd James Bond Coming May 2, 2008! |work=[[Superhero Hype!]] |date=2006-07-20 |url=http://www.superherohype.com/news/jamesbondnews.php?id=4521 |accessdate=2007-08-06}}</ref> [[Roger Michell]], who directed Craig in ''[[Enduring Love (film)|Enduring Love]]'' and ''[[The Mother (film)|The Mother]]'', was in negotiations to direct, but opted out because there was no script.<ref>{{cite news |title=They call him Director No|work=[[The Times]]|date=2007-07-04|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/stage/theatre/article1877785.ece|accessdate=2008-01-27 | location=London}}</ref> Sony Entertainment vice-chairman Jeff Blake admitted a production schedule of eighteen months was a very short window, and the release date was pushed back to late 2008.<ref name=superherohype>{{cite news |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=16308 |title=Bond 22 Targeting November 7, 2008 |work= [[Superhero Hype!]] |date=2006-09-01|accessdate=2006-09-01}}</ref> [[Neal Purvis]] and [[Robert Wade (screenwriter)|Robert Wade]] completed their draft of the script by April 2007,<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Fleming|title='Barbarella' back in action|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=2007-04-11|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117962920.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|accessdate=2007-08-06}}</ref> and [[Paul Haggis]] &ndash; who polished the ''Casino Royale'' script &ndash; began his rewrite the next month.<ref>{{cite news |title=Paul Haggis on board to work on Bond 22 script, but turns down directing role |work=[[MI6.co.uk]] |date=2007-05-23|url=http://www.mi6.co.uk/news/index.php?itemid=5040&catid=106 |accessdate=2007-05-23}}</ref>

In June 2007, [[Marc Forster]] was confirmed as director.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003600629 |title=Forster back in action with 'Bond 22' |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=2007-06-20 |accessdate=2007-06-19}}</ref> He was surprised that he was approached for the job, stating he was not a big Bond film fan through the years, and that he would not have accepted the project had he not seen ''Casino Royale'' prior to making his decision: he felt Bond had been humanised in that film, arguing since traveling the world had become less exotic since the series' advent, it made sense to focus more on Bond as a character. Born in Germany and raised in [[Switzerland]], Forster was the first Bond director not to come from the [[British Commonwealth of Nations]], although he noted Bond's mother is Swiss, making him somewhat appropriate to handle the British icon.<ref name=swiss>{{cite news |author=Terrence Rafferty |title=A License to Pursue the Inner Bond |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2007-12-09|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/09/movies/09raff.html?_r=2&ref=movies&oref=slogin&oref=slogin |accessdate=2007-12-09}}</ref> The director collaborated strongly with [[Barbara Broccoli]] and Michael G. Wilson, noting they only blocked two very expensive ideas he had.<ref name=diary22/> The director found ''Casino Royale''{{'}}s 144 minute running time too long, and wanted his follow-up to be "tight and fast [...] like a bullet."<ref name=bullet>{{cite news|author=Alistair Harkness|title=A Quantum leap|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=2008-10-30|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/A-Quantum-leap.4643021.jp|accessdate=2008-10-30}}</ref>

{{quote|"Because Bond plays it real, I thought the political circumstances should be real too, even though Bond shouldn't be a political film. I thought the more political I make it, the more real it feels, not just with Bolivia and what's happening in Haiti, but with all these corporations like Shell and Chevron saying they're green because it's so fashionable to be green. During the Cold War, everything was very clear, the good guys and the bad guys. Today there's much overlapping of good and bad. It isn't as morally distinct, because we all have both elements in us."|&ndash;Marc Forster on the political landscape of the film.<ref name=pain/>}}

Haggis, Forster and Wilson rewrote the story from scratch.<ref name=zetumer/> Haggis said he completed his script two hours before the [[2007–2008 Writers Guild of America strike]] officially began.<ref name=swiss/> Forster noted a running theme in his films were emotionally repressed protagonists, and the theme of the picture would be Bond learning to trust after feeling betrayed by Vesper.<ref name=mi6forster/> Forster said he created the Camille character as a strong female counterpart to Bond rather than a casual love interest: she openly shows emotions similar to those which Bond experiences but is unable to express.<ref name=ignqa>{{cite news|url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/911/911930p1.htm|author=Jim Vejvoda|title=007 Responds to IGN Readers|work=[[IGN]]|date=2008-09-22|accessdate=2008-09-22}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Haggis located his draft's climax in the [[Swiss Alps]],<ref name=empire>{{cite news|author=Ian Nathan|title=Quantum's Leap|work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]|month=October | year=2008|pages=82 &ndash; 90}}</ref> but Forster wanted the action sequences to be based around the four [[classical element]]s of earth, water, air and fire.<ref name=variety>{{cite news|author=[[Anne Thompson]]|title='Solace' offers thinking person's 007|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=2008-10-23|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117994573.html?categoryid=2508&cs=1|accessdate=2008-11-01}}</ref> The decision to homage ''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]'' in Fields's death came about as Forster wanted to show oil had replaced gold as the most precious material.<ref name=pain>{{cite news|author=Ciaran Carty|title='I felt there was pain in Bond'|work=[[Sunday Tribune]]|date=2008-11-02|url=http://www.tribune.ie/arts/films/article/2008/nov/02/i-felt-there-was-pain-in-bond/|accessdate=2008-11-02}}</ref> The producers rejected Haggis's idea that Vesper Lynd had a child, because "Bond was an orphan [...] Once he finds the kid, Bond can't just leave the kid."<ref>{{cite news|author=Logan Hill|title=How James Bond Nearly Became a Father|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=2008-11-03|url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2008/11/how_james_bond_nearly_became_a.html|accessdate=2008-11-03}}</ref>

Michael G. Wilson decided on the film's title ''[[wikt:quantum|Quantum]] of [[wikt:solace|Solace]]'' only "a few days" before its announcement on 24 January 2008.<ref name=bbctitle>{{cite news |title=New Bond film title is confirmed |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=2008-01-24 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7206997.stm |accessdate=2008-01-24}}</ref> It was the name of a short story in [[Ian Fleming]]'s anthology ''[[For Your Eyes Only (short story collection)|For Your Eyes Only]]'' (1960).<ref name=confuse/>  The film is related to the title in one of its thematic elements: "...when the 'Quantum of Solace' drops to zero, humanity and consideration of one human for another is gone."<ref>See, Wikipedia,''[[For Your Eyes Only (short story collection)|For Your Eyes Only]]''http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/For_Your_Eyes_Only_%28short_story_collection%29 (as of March 9, 2010, 01:50 GMT)</ref> Daniel Craig admitted, "I was unsure at first. Bond is looking for his quantum of solace and that's what he wants, he wants his closure. Ian Fleming says that if you don't have a quantum of solace in your relationship then the relationship is over. It's that spark of niceness in a relationship that if you don't have you might as well give up."<ref name=guardian/> He said that "Bond doesn't have that because his girlfriend [Vesper Lynd] has been killed,"<ref name=confuse>{{cite news |title=Daniel: the title is meant to confuse |work=[[Press and Journal (Scotland)|Press and Journal]] |date=2008-01-24}}</ref> and therefore, "[Bond is] looking for revenge [...] to make himself happy with the world again."<ref name=bbctitle/> Afterwards, Quantum was made the name of the organisation introduced in ''Casino Royale''.<ref name=quantum/> Craig noted the letter Q itself looks rather odd.<ref name=criminal/> Near the end of the film, the Camille Montes character and Bond have a discussion about their individual quests to avenge the deaths of their loved ones. Montes asks Bond to "let me know what it feels like" when he succeeds, the implication of the title being that it will be a small amount of solace compared to his despair. Bond's lack of emotion when he does exact revenge shows this to be the case.

During filming, after the strike ended, Forster read a [[spec script]] by [[Joshua Zetumer]], which he liked, and hired him to reshape scenes for the later parts of the shoot, which the director was still unsatisfied with.<ref name=zetumer>{{cite news | title = A James Bond Set Visit and Seven Exclusive Quantum of Solace Images!  | work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | date = 2008-04-04 | url = http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/news/1719930/a_james_bond_set_visit_and_seven_exclusive_quantum_of_solace_images | accessdate=2008-04-05}}</ref> Forster had the actors rehearse their scenes, as he liked to film scenes continually.<ref name=environment>{{cite news | author = Karl Rozemeyer | title = Mathieu Amalric on Being the 'Bond 22' Villain | work = [[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]] | date = 2008-03-18 | url = http://www.premiere.com/features/4455/mathieu-amalric-on-being-the-bond-22-villain.html | accessdate=2008-03-19}}</ref> Zetumer rewrote dialogue depending on the actors' ideas each day.<ref name=environment/>

===Filming===
''Quantum of Solace'' was shot in six countries,<ref name=artfilm>{{cite news|author=Randee Dawn|title='Quantum' is Marc Forster's 007 art film|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=2008-11-11|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3ie9098baec9eb95cd02a01aebbd96a968|accessdate=2008-11-13}}</ref> [[Second unit]] filming began in Italy at the [[Palio di Siena]] horse race on 16 August 2007:<ref name=paliodisiena>{{cite news|author=Richard Owen|title=Bond has activists on his tail over new film's 'brutal' horse race finale|work= [[The Times]]|date=2007-08-13|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article2246486.ece|accessdate= 2007-08-13 | location=London}}</ref> though at this point Forster was unsure how it would fit into the film.<ref name=variety/> Some scenes were filmed also in [[Maratea]] and [[Craco]], two little and characteristics towns in [[Basilicata]].<ref>{{cite news|author=www.imdb.com|title=Filming locations for Quantum of Solace|work=|date=2008-11-11|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0830515/locations|accessdate=2009-06-02}}</ref> Other places used for location shooting were [[Madrid]] in August 2007;<ref>{{cite news |title=Bond 22 filming takes place in Madrid, Spain during last week of August|work=[[MI6.co.uk]] |date=2007-08-31|url=http://www.mi6.co.uk/news/index.php?itemid=5327 |accessdate=2008-03-25}}</ref> [[Baja California]], [[Mexico]] in early 2008, for shots of the aerial battle;<ref name=dogfight>{{cite news | title = Newswrap #2 video | work=[[ReelzChannel]] | date = 2008-03-20 | url = http://www.reelzchannel.com/movie/233698/quantum-of-solace?clipid=32934 | accessdate=2008-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = David Allen | title = A bond with Chino | publisher = [[Los Angeles Newspaper Group]] | date = 2008-02-28 | url = http://www.dailybulletin.com/ci_8399719 | accessdate=2008-03-02}}</ref> [[Malcesine]], [[Limone sul Garda]] and [[Tremosine]] in Italy during March,<ref name=siena>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (16) | work = [[MI6.co.uk]] | date = 2008-03-17 | url = http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary16.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=2008-03-20}}</ref> and at [[Talamone]] during the end of April.<ref name=fountain>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (19) | work = [[MI6.co.uk]] | date = 2008-03-27 | url = http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary19.php3?t=&s= | accessdate=2008-03-28}}</ref> The main unit began on 3 January 2008,<ref name=diary22/> at [[Pinewood Studios]]. The [[007 Stage]] was used for the fight in the art gallery,<ref name=guardian>{{cite news |author=Mark Brown|title=Everything changes but Bond |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2008-01-24 |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2008/jan/24/features|accessdate=2008-01-24 | location=London}}</ref> and an MI6 safehouse hidden within the city's [[cistern]]s,<ref name=bbcbts>{{cite news |author=Tim Marsters |title=Behind the scenes on the Bond set |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=2008-01-25|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7208410.stm |accessdate=2008-01-25}}</ref> while other stages housed Bond's Bolivian hotel suite,<ref name=modernism/> and the MI6 headquarters.<ref name=bbcbts/> Interior and exterior airport scenes were filmed at [[Farnborough Airfield]] and the snowy closing scenes were filmed at the Bruneval Barracks in [[Aldershot]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.gethampshire.co.uk/news/s/2038353_barracks_and_airport_provide_location_for_bond_film | title = Barracks and airport provide location for Bond film | accessdate = 2008-11-18 | author = Rebecca Connop Price | date = 2008-10-30 | work = Get Hampshire}}</ref>

[[File:Quantum Of Solace Shelter Bay.jpg|thumb|Marine shooting being carried out at [[Fort Sherman]]]]

Shooting in [[Panama City]] began on 7 February 2008 at [[Howard Air Force Base]]. The country doubled for Haiti and Bolivia, with the [[National Institute of Culture of Panama]] standing in for a hotel in the latter country. A sequence requiring several hundred [[extra (actor)|extra]]s was also shot at nearby [[Colón, Panama|Colón]].<ref name=andeanhotel>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (11) | work = [[MI6.co.uk]] | date = 2008-02-09 | url = http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary11.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=2008-02-09}}</ref> Shooting in Panama was also carried out at [[Fort Sherman]], a former US military base on the Colón coast. Forster was disappointed he could only shoot the boat chase in that harbour, as he had a more spectacular vision for the scene.<ref name=comingsoon>{{cite news|author=Edward Douglas|title=Marc Forster Finds His Quantum of Solace|work=ComingSoon.net|date=2008-11-10|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=50314|accessdate=2008-11-10}}</ref> Officials in the country worked with the locals to "minimise inconvenience" for the cast and crew, and in return hoped the city's exposure in the film would increase tourism.<ref name=proddiarynine>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (9) | work = [[MI6.co.uk]] | date = 2008-02-02 | url = http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary09.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=2008-02-08}}</ref> The crew was going to move to [[Cusco]], [[Peru]] for ten days of filming on 2 March,<ref name=andeanhotel/> but the location was cancelled for budget reasons.<ref name=artfilm/> Twelve days of filming in [[Chile]] began on 24 March at [[Antofagasta]]. There was shooting in [[Cobija, Chile|Cobija]], the [[Paranal Observatory]], and other locations in the [[Atacama Desert]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (17) | work = [[MI6.co.uk]] | date = 2008-03-19 | url = http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary17.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=2008-03-20}}</ref> Forster chose the desert and the observatory's [[ESO Hotel]] to represent Bond's rigid emotions, and being on the verge of committing a vengeful act as he confronts Greene in the film's climax.<ref name=quantum>{{cite news | title = Seeking Solace on the Bond set | work = [[USA Today]] | date = 2008-04-03 | url = http://www.usatoday.com/life/flash.htm?gid=459 | accessdate=2008-04-04}}</ref><ref name=water/>
[[File:Paranal camp.jpg|thumb|left|Marc Forster chose the Atacama Desert to represent Bond's vengefulness in the climax]]
While filming in [[Sierra Gorda]], Chile, the local mayor, Carlos Lopez, staged a protest because he was angry at the filmmakers' portrayal of the Antofagasta region as part of Bolivia, as it had been invaded and occupied by the Chilean army in 1883. He was arrested, detained briefly, and put on trial two days later. EON dismissed his claim that they needed his permission to film in the area.<ref>{{cite news | author = Simon Gardner | title = James Bond has new nemesis: irate Chilean mayor | publisher=Reuters | date = 2008-04-02 | url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/topNews/idUKN0237294620080402 | accessdate=2008-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = 'Mayor' protests on Chile 007 set | work = [[BBC News Online]] | date = 2008-04-02 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7326582.stm | accessdate=2008-04-03}}</ref> Michael G. Wilson also explained Bolivia was appropriate to the plot, because of the country's history of water problems,<ref name=water>{{cite news |author=Anthony Breznican |title=James Bond series takes a 'Quantum' leap |work=[[USA Today]] |date=2008-04-04|url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2008-04-03-bond-quantum_N.htm |accessdate=2008-04-04}}</ref> and was surprised the two countries disliked each other a century after the [[War of the Pacific]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (22) | work = [[MI6.co.uk]] | date = 2008-04-07 | url = http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary22.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=2008-04-10}}</ref> In a poll by Chilean daily newspaper ''[[La Segunda]]'', 75% of its readers disagreed with Lopez's actions, due to the negative image they felt it presented of Chile, and the controversy's potential to put off productions looking to film in the country in the future.<ref>{{cite news | title = ¿Apoya Ud. las protestas del alcalde de Sierra Gorda por la filmación de James Bond en su comuna? | work = [[La Segunda]] | date = 2008-03-02 | url = http://www.lasegunda.com/edicionOnline/interaccion/encuestas/resultado.asp?idencuesta=2512&idclasificacion=3&fg= | language=Spanish | accessdate=2008-04-02}}</ref>

From 4&ndash;12 April, the main unit shot on Sienese rooftops.<ref name=fountain/> Shooting on the real rooftops turned out to be less expensive than building them at Pinewood.<ref name=artfilm/> The next four weeks were scheduled for filming the car chase at [[Lake Garda]] and [[Carrara]].<ref name=fountain/> On 19 April, an [[Aston Martin]] employee driving a [[Aston Martin DBS V12|DBS]] to the set crashed into the lake. He survived, and was fined £400 for reckless driving.<ref>{{cite news | author = Nick Pisa | title = Driver of James Bond's Aston Martin cheated death in dramatic crash | work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] | date = 2008-04-22}}</ref> Another accident occurred on 21 April, and two days later, two stuntmen were seriously injured, with one, Greek stuntman Aris Comninos, having to be put in intensive care. Filming of the scenes was temporarily halted so that Italian police could investigate the causes of the accidents.<ref>{{cite news | author = Paul Bompard | title = James Bond production halted amid fears of a curse | work = [[The Times]] | date = 2008-04-24 | url = ghttp://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article3810782.ece | accessdate=2008-04-24 | location=London}}</ref> Stunt co-ordinator Gary Powell said the accidents were a testament to the realism of the action.<ref name=empire/> Rumours of a "curse" spread among tabloid media, something which deeply offended Craig, who disliked that they compared Comninos' accident to something like his minor finger injury later on the shoot (also part of the "curse"). Comninos recovered safely from his injury.<ref name=criminal/>

[[File:BregenzToscaBühnenbild4.JPG|thumb|Preparations for the performance of ''[[Tosca]]'' at [[Bregenzer Festspiele]]]]
Filming took place at the [[Bregenzer Festspiele|floating opera stage]] at [[Bregenz]], [[Austria]] from 28 April&ndash;9 May 2008. The sequence, where Bond stalks the villains during a performance of ''[[Tosca]]'', required 1500 extras.<ref>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (10) | work = [[MI6.co.uk]] | date = 2008-02-08 | url = http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary10.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=2008-02-09}}</ref> The production used a large model of an eye, which Forster felt fitted in the Bond style, and the opera itself has parallels to the film.<ref name=lake>{{cite news|title=Solace on the Lake|work=[[MSN]]|date=2008-05-08|url=http://movies.msn.com/movies/hitlist/05-13-08|accessdate=2008-05-16}}</ref> A short driving sequence was filmed at the nearby [[Feldkirch, Vorarlberg]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Production Diary (1) |work=[[MI6.co.uk]] |date=2008-01-03|url=http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary01.php3?t=&s=articles |accessdate=2008-01-08}}</ref> The crew returned to Italy from 13&ndash;17 May to shoot a (planned) car crash at the marble quarry in Carrara,<ref>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (32) | work = [[MI6.co.uk]] | date = 2008-05-16 | url = http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary32.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=2008-05-16}}</ref> and a recreation of the Palio di Siena at the [[Piazza del Campo]] in Siena. 1000 extras were hired for a scene where Bond emerges from the ''Fonte Gaia''. Originally, he would have emerged from the city's cisterns at [[Siena Cathedral]], but this was thought disrespectful.<ref name=fountain/> By June, the crew returned to Pinewood for four weeks,<ref name=lake/> where new sets (including the interior of the hotel in the climax) were built.<ref name=zetumer/><ref name=modernism/> The [[wrap (filmmaking)|wrap]] party was held on 21 June.<ref>{{cite news | title = `Quantum of Solace` wrap party held on Saturday night, David Arnold confirms | work = [[MI6.co.uk]] | date = 2008-06-22 | url = http://www.mi6.co.uk/news/index.php?itemid=6394 | accessdate=2008-06-22}}</ref>

===Design===
Production designer [[Peter Lamont]], a crew member on eighteen previous Bond films, retired after ''Casino Royale''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Peter Lamont bows out from Bond 22, Dennis Gassner to be Production Designer |work=[[MI6.co.uk]] |date=2007-07-23|url=http://www.mi6.co.uk/news/index.php?itemid=5206 |accessdate=2007-07-23}}</ref> Forster hired [[Dennis Gassner]] in his stead, having admired his work on ''[[The Truman Show]]'' and the films of the [[Coen brothers]].<ref name=mi6forster>{{cite web|url=http://mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/bond_22_qos_capsule_forster.php3?t=qos&s=qos&id=02080|title=Marc Forster on directing 007|work=[[MI6.co.uk]]|date=2008-11-11|accessdate=2008-11-13}}</ref> Craig said the film would have "a touch of [[Ken Adam]],"<ref name=kenadam>{{cite news |author=Olly Richards |title=Daniel Craig Talks Quantum of Solace |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |date=2008-01-24 |url=http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=21855 |accessdate=2008-01-24}}</ref> while Michael G. Wilson also called Gassner's designs "a [[postmodern]] look at [[modernism]]."<ref name=modernism>{{cite news|title=Quantum of Solace - Production Diary (7)|work=[[MI6.co.uk]]|date=2008-01-26|url=http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary07.php3?t=&s=|accessdate=2008-01-26}}</ref> Forster said he felt the early Bond films' design "were ahead of their time,"<ref name=mi6forster/> and enjoyed the clashing of an older style with his own because it created a unique look unto itself.<ref name=aicnqa/> Gassner wanted his sets to emphasise Craig's "great angular, textured face and wonderful blue eyes," and totally redesigned the MI6 headquarters because he felt Judi Dench "was a bit tired in the last film, so I thought, let’s bring her into a new world."<ref>{{cite news|title=James Bond: licence to redesign|work=[[Maclean's]]|date=2008-11-17|url=http://blog.macleans.ca/2008/11/17/james-bond-licence-to-redesign/|accessdate=2008-11-18}}</ref>

Louise Frogley replaced [[Lindy Hemming]] as [[costume design]]er, though Hemming remained as supervisor. Hemming hired [[Brioni]] for Bond's suits since her tenure on the series began with 1995's ''[[GoldenEye]]'', but Lindsay Pugh, another supervisor, explained their suits were "too relaxed." [[Tom Ford]] was hired to tailor "sharper" suits for Craig. Pugh said the costumes aimed towards the 1960s feel, especially for Bond and Fields. [[Prada]] provided the dresses for both Bond girls. [[Jasper Conran]] designed Camille's ginger bandeau, bronze skirt and gold fish necklace,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jasperconran.com/collections/womenswear/archive/james-bond,116,ART.html |title=Jasper Conran Spring Summer 2008 Collection |publisher=Jasperconran.com |date= |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> while [[Chrome Hearts]] designed gothic jewellery for Amalric's character, which the actor liked enough to keep after filming.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jessica Fellowes|title=James Bond week: 007 and his girls are back with a crisp new look|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=2008-10-22|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/main.jhtml?xml=/fashion/2008/10/22/efbond322.xml|accessdate=2008-10-25 | location=London}}</ref> Sophie Harley, who created [[Vesper Lynd]]'s earrings and [[Algeria]]n loveknot necklace in ''Casino Royale'', was called upon to create another version of the necklace.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jessica Fellowes|title=Necklace with a starring role|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=2008-10-22|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/main.jhtml?xml=/fashion/2008/10/22/efbond222.xml|accessdate=2008-10-25 | location=London}}</ref>

The film returns to the traditional [[James Bond gun barrel sequence|gun barrel opening shot]], which was altered into part of the story for ''Casino Royale'' where it was moved to the end of the title sequence. In this film the gun barrel sequence was moved to the end of the movie, which Wilson explained was done for a surprise,<ref>{{cite news|author=Mark Caro|title=James Bond: 15 facts to know now|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=2008-11-09|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/features/arts/chi-bond-1109-covernov09,0,4869399.story|accessdate=2008-11-08}}</ref> and to signify the conclusion of the story begun in the previous film. The opening credits sequence was created by [[MK12]]; Having worked on Forster's ''[[Stranger than Fiction (2006 film)|Stranger than Fiction]]'' and ''[[The Kite Runner (film)|The Kite Runner]]'', MK12 spontaneously began developing the sequence early on in production, and had a good idea of its appearance which meant it did not have to be redone when the [[#Music|title singer]] was changed. MK12 selected various [[twilight]] colours to represent Bond's mood and focused on a dot motif based on the gunbarrel shot. MK12 also worked on scenes with [[graphical user interface]], including the electronic table MI6 use,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://vfxworld.com/index.php?atype=articles&id=3881|author=Bill Desowitz|title=MK12 Has a Blast with Quantum Main Titles|work=VFXWorld|date=2009-01-16|accessdate=2009-01-26}}</ref> and the [[Port-au-Prince]], [[Haiti]] title cards.<ref>{{cite news|author=Yves Peters|title=MK12 Create Custom Type for Quantum of Solace Title Sequence|work=The Font Feed|publisher=[[FontShop]]|date=2008-12-19|url=http://fontfeed.com/archives/mk12-quantum-of-solace-title-sequence/|accessdate=2008-12-22}}</ref>

===Effects===
[[File:AstonMartinDBSCC08.jpg|thumb|right|[[Aston Martin DBS V12]] on display at the 2008 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]]]]
''Quantum of Solace'' was the last in [[Ford Motor Company|Ford Motor]]'s three-film deal that began with 2002's ''[[Die Another Day]]''. Although Ford sold over 90% of the [[Aston Martin]] company in 2007, the [[Aston Martin DBS V12]] returned for the film's car chase around Lake Garda;<ref>{{cite news |title=Aston Martin DBS to star in new James Bond film |work=[[Aston Martin]] |year=2007 |url=http://www.astonmartin.com/thecompany/news?a=14d34f22-1324-4ca5-acbb-764f80c7d7f2 |accessdate=2007-12-11}}</ref> [[Dan Bradley]] was hired as [[second unit]] director because of his work on the second and third [[Bourne (film series)|''Bourne'' films]], so the film would continue the gritty action style begun in ''Casino Royale''.<ref>{{cite news |author=Borys Kit |title=Bradley tapped to aid Bond stunts |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=2007-09-04 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i61cdc71247ef46a7ec4bddbba9463397 |accessdate=2008-01-10}}</ref> He had intended to use [[Ford GT]]s for the opening chase,<ref>{{cite web |title=Dan Bradley interview |work=Bourne Stunt Simulator |url=http://www.bournestuntsimulator.com/danbradley/ |accessdate=2008-01-16}}</ref> but it was replaced by the [[Alfa Romeo 159]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1902288/James-Bond-filming-suspended-after-third-accident-leaves-stuntman-in-coma.html|title=James Bond filming suspended after third accident leaves stuntman in coma|accessdate=2008-04-28|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=2008-04-28 | location=London | first=Malcolm | last=Moore}}</ref> After location filming in Italy, further close-ups of Craig, the cars and the truck were shot at Pinewood against a bluescreen.<ref name=vfxworld>{{cite news|author=Bill Desowitz|title=A Quantum of VFX for James Bond|work=VFX World|date=2008-12-03|url=http://vfxworld.com/?atype=articles&id=3844&page=1#|accessdate=2008-12-04}}</ref> Originally three Alfa Romeos were in the sequence: but Forster felt the scene was running too long and re-edited the scene so it only looked like two Romeos were chasing Bond.<ref name=fxguide/> Six Aston Martins were destroyed during filming, and one of them was purchased by a fan.<ref name=criminal/>

Fourteen cameras were used to film the [[Palio di Siena]], footage which was later edited into the main sequence. Aerial shots using helicopters were banned, and the crew were also forbidden from showing any violence "involving either people or animals."<ref name=paliodisiena/> To shoot the foot chase in [[Siena]] in April 2008 four camera cranes were built in the town, and a [[Skycam|cable camera]] was also used.<ref name=siena/> [[Framestore]] worked on the Siena chase, duplicating the 1000 extras during principal photography to match shots of the 40,000 strong audience at the real Palio, removing wires that held Craig and the stuntmen in the rooftop segment of the chase, and digital expansion of the floor and skylight in the art gallery Bond and Mitchell fall into.<ref name=vfxworld/> The art gallery fight was intended to be simple, but during filming Craig's stunt double accidentally fell from the construction scaffolding. Forster preferred the idea of Bond hanging from ropes reaching for his gun to kill Mitchell, rather than having both men run out of the building to continue their chase as specified in the script, and the number of effects shots increased.<ref name=vfxworld/>

To film the aerial dogfight, a "Snakehead" camera was built and placed on the nose and tail of a [[Piper Aerostar]] 700. [[SolidWorks]], who provided the software used to design the camera, stated "pilots for the first time can fly as aggressively as they dare without sacrificing the drama of the shot." The camera could turn 360 degrees and was shaped like a [[periscope]].<ref>{{cite news | author = Chris Reidy | title = "Snakehead" films James Bond dogfight footage | work = [[The Boston Globe]] | date = 2008-05-12 | url =  http://www.boston.com/business/ticker/2008/05/_the_concord_of.html | accessdate=2008-05-12}}</ref> The crew also mounted SpaceCams on helicopters, and placed cameras with 1600&nbsp;mm lenses underground, to cover the action.<ref name=dogfight/> Forster wanted to film the planefight as a homage to [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s ''[[North by Northwest]]'', and chose planes like the [[Douglas DC-3]] to suit that.<ref name=aicnqa>{{cite news|title=Capone talks with James Bond himself, Daniel Craig, and Quantum of Solace director Marc Forster in London!!!|work=[[Ain't It Cool News]]|date=2008-09-21|url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/38427|accessdate=2008-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = For Your Eyes Only: RT in Austria with James Bond | work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | date = 2008-05-09 | url = http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/news/1727255/2/for_your_eyes_only_rt_in_austria_with_james_bond | accessdate=2008-05-16}}</ref> 

The [[free-fall]] scene involved its own set of challenges, Craig disliked the idea of "being hung by wires and blown by a large fan in front of a green screen" but actual [[sky diving]] coverage has serious drawbacks. It’s not only difficult, dangerous and time-consuming, but nearly always results in problematic head-replacements for close-ups. Stunt co-ordinator Gary Powell and VFX Designer Kevin Tod Haug, presented the idea of filming the scene in a large [[vertical wind tunnel]] in [[Bedford]] in order to do this sequence as practically as possible.  
While a great solution for the actors’ performances the technique presented enormous VFX challenges: relighting shots captured in a tall white tube to match the sky over the Bolivian desert, and the impossibility of filming medium to wide shots of the actors. An array of eight [[Dalsa Origin]] cameras (supported by 7 HD cameras and a 35mm hand-held camera, all running in sync) was used to create a [[virtual camera]] with which to shoot the actors floating in the simulator. Ged Wright and his team at [[Double Negative (VFX)|Double Negative]]<ref name=fxguide/> developed a method to use the data from these cameras that allowed these real performances to be placed in a synthetic environment as seen by a synthetic camera.   
During the shooting in the wind tunnel Craig and Kurylenko wore wind-resistant contact lenses that enabled them to open their eyes as they fell. For safety and comfort, they only shot for thirty seconds at a time.<ref name=ugoqa>{{cite news|url=http://movieblog.ugo.com/index.php/movieblog/more/your_quantum_of_solace_questions_answered/|title=Your Quantum of Solace Questions Answered!|work=[[UGO Networks]]|date=2008-09-21|accessdate=2008-09-22}}</ref> Forster wished he had more time to work on the free-fall scene.<ref name=vfxworld/>

The [[Moving Picture Company]] created the climactic hotel sequence. The fire effects were supervised by [[Chris Corbould]], and post-production MPC had to enhance the sequence by making the smoke look closer to the actors, so it would look more dangerous.<ref name=vfxworld/> A full-scale replica of the building's exterior was used for the exploding part Bond and Camille escape from. 
The boat chase was another scene that required very little CGI. Machine FX worked on replacing a few shots of visible stuntmen with a digital version of Craig's head,<ref name=fxguide/> and recreated the boats Bond jumps over on his motorcycle to make it look more dangerous.<ref name=vfxworld/> Crowd creation was done for the ''[[Tosca]]'' scene by Machine FX, to make the performance look like it had sold out.<ref name=fxguide>{{cite news|title=Back into Bondage|date=2008-11-16|author=Bill Dawes|work=[[fxguide]]|url=http://www.fxguide.com/article508.html|accessdate=2008-11-22}}</ref> Forster edited the opera scene to resemble ''[[The Man Who Knew Too Much (1956 film)|The Man Who Knew Too Much]]''.<ref name=comingsoon/> In total, there are 900+ visual effects shots in ''Quantum of Solace''.<ref name=vfxworld/>

===Music===
{{Main|Quantum of Solace (soundtrack)}}
[[David Arnold]], who composed the scores for the previous four Bond films, returned for ''Quantum of Solace''. He said that Forster likes to work very closely with his composers and that, in comparison to the accelerated schedule he was tied to on ''Casino Royale'', the intention was to spend a long time scoring the film to "really work it out." He also said he would be "taking a different approach" with the score.<ref>{{cite video | people=Tommy Pearson, [[David Arnold]] |date=November year 2007 title=Interview with David Arnold| url=http://www.stageandscreenonline.com/_Media/DavidArnoldPart3.mp3 |format=mp3 | medium=Audio interview | work=Stage and Screen Online |accessdate=2008-04-25 }}</ref> Arnold composed the music based on impressions from reading the script, and Forster edited those into the film.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mark Beaumont|title=The Midas touch of David Arnold and his influence on Bond|work=[[The Times]]|date=2008-10-18|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article4948366.ece|accessdate=2008-10-18 | location=London}}</ref> As with ''Casino Royale'', Arnold kept use of the [[James Bond Theme]] to a minimum.<ref name=variety/> Arnold collaborated with [[Kieran Hebden]] for "Crawl, End Crawl," a remix of the score played during the end credits.<ref>{{cite news|title=`Crawl, End Crawl` track from `Quantum of Solace` now on iTunes|work=[[MI6.co.uk]]|date=2008-12-09|url=http://www.mi6.co.uk/news/index.php?itemid=7146&t=mi6&s=news|accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref>

[[Jack White (musician)|Jack White]] of [[The White Stripes]] and [[Alicia Keys]] collaborated on "[[Another Way to Die]]," the first Bond music duet.<ref>{{cite news | title = Alicia Keys, Jack White Team For Bond Theme | work = ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' | date = 2008-07-29 | url = http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003832786 | accessdate=2008-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Quantum of Solace - News - Alicia Keys, Jack White Team For "Quantum of Solace" Theme Song (Press Release) | publisher = [[Columbia Pictures]] | date = 2008-07-29 | url = http://www.007.com/download/ThemeSong_QOS_PressRelease.pdf | accessdate=2008-08-02|format=PDF}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> They had wanted to work together for two years beforehand.<ref name=memphishorns/> The song was recorded in [[Nashville, Tennessee]]; White played the drums while Keys performed on the piano.<ref name=newduo>{{cite news|author=Brian Hiatt|title=Jack White and Alicia Keys: Bond's New Duo|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=2008-10-02|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/23064110/jack_white_and_alicia_keys_bonds_new_duo|accessdate=2008-09-16}}</ref> [[The Memphis Horns]] also contributed to the track.<ref name=memphishorns>{{cite news|title=Jack White Talks Bond|work=[[IGN]]|date=2008-08-21|url=http://uk.music.ign.com/articles/901/901612p1.html|accessdate=2008-08-21}}</ref> White's favourite Bond theme is [[John Barry (composer)|John Barry]]'s instrumental piece for ''[[On Her Majesty's Secret Service (soundtrack)|On Her Majesty's Secret Service]]'', and he watched various opening credit sequences from the series for inspiration while mixing the track.<ref name=newduo/> [[Mark Ronson]] and [[Amy Winehouse]] had recorded a [[demo (music)|demo]] track for the film,<ref>{{cite news | title = Winehouse working on 'Bond theme' | work = [[BBC News Online]] | date = 2008-04-28 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7371949.stm | accessdate=2008-04-28}}</ref> but Ronson explained Winehouse's well-publicised legal issues in the preceding weeks made her "not ready to record any music" at that time.<ref>{{cite news | title = Troubled Winehouse 'not ready' for Bond theme | publisher = CNN/[[Associated Press|AP]] | date =2008-05-03 | accessdate=2008-05-03 | url = http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Music/05/03/winehouse.bond.ap/index.html |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080506020030/http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Music/05/03/winehouse.bond.ap/index.html |archivedate = May 6, 2008}}</ref>

==Release==
The film premiered at the [[Odeon Leicester Square]] on 29 October 2008. Princes [[Prince William of Wales|William]] and [[Prince Henry of Wales|Harry]] of Wales attended, and proceeds from the screening were donated to the charities [[Help for Heroes]] and [[the Royal British Legion]].<ref>{{cite news|title="Quantum of Solace" World Premiere Announced|work=[[MI6.co.uk]]|date=2008-08-05|url=http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/bond_22_premiere_announced.php3?t=qos&s=qos&id=01974|accessdate=2008-08-06}}</ref> The film was originally scheduled to be released in the UK and North America on 7 November; however, EON pushed forward the British date to 31 October during filming,<ref>{{cite news | author = Olly Richards | title = Quantum of Solace Gets Earlier Release | work = [[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] | date = 2008-03-19 | url = http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=22223 | accessdate=2008-03-19}}</ref> while the American date was pushed back in August to 14 November, after ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'' had been moved to 2009, thereby allowing the distributors to market the film over the Fall blockbuster [[Thanksgiving]] holiday weekend.<ref>{{cite news|author=Columbia Pictures|title=Quantum of Solace Moved Back a Week|work=ComingSoon.net|date=2008-08-21|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=48142|accessdate=2008-08-21}}</ref> In Australia, the film was moved a week to 19 November, after [[20th Century Fox]] chose to release ''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]'' on ''Quantum of Solace''{{'}}s original date of 26 November.<ref>{{cite news|author=Garry Maddox|title=Bond blinks first in battle of blockbusters|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=2008-09-06|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/film/bond-blinks-first-in-battle-of-the-blockbusters/2008/09/05/1220121520755.html|accessdate=2008-09-06}}</ref>

===Marketing===
Returning [[product placement]] partners from ''Casino Royale'' included [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]], [[Heineken Pilsener]], [[Smirnoff]], [[Omega SA]], [[Virgin Atlantic Airways]] and [[Sony Ericsson]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Marc Graser|title=Brands line up for Bond sequel|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=2008-08-14|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117990584.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|accessdate=2008-08-15}}</ref> A reported £50 million was earned in product placement, which tops the Bond film's record of £44 million for ''Die Another Day''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve McGinty|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/Does-this-mean-Bond39s-past.4630875.jp|title=Does this mean Bond's past his sell-by date?|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=2008-10-27|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref> The 2009 [[Ford Ka]] is driven by Camille in the film.<ref>"[http://www.mi6.co.uk/news/index.php?itemid=6802&catid=106&t=mi6&s=news Bond girl Olga Kurylenko introduces Ford Ka at Paris Motor Show (video)]," ''[[MI6.co.uk]]'' (2008-03-10). Retrieved on 2008-11-08.</ref> [[Avon Products|Avon]] created a fragrance called Bond Girl 007 with [[Gemma Arterton]] as the "face" of the product.<ref>{{cite news|title=Avon to introduce Bond Girl 007 fragrance with Gemma Arterton|work=[[MI6.co.uk]]|date=2008-05-23|url=http://www.mi6.co.uk/news/index.php?itemid=6273|accessdate=2008-08-12}}</ref> [[Coca-Cola]] became a promotional partner, rebranding [[Coke Zero]] as "Coke Zero Zero 7." A tie-in advert featured the orchestral element of "Another Way to Die."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/video/2008/sep/11/advertising.jamesbond|title="Coca-Cola launches ad featuring Jack White's Quantum of Solace music"|work=[[The Guardian]]|author=Mark Sweney|date=2008-09-11|accessdate=2008-09-18 | location=London}}</ref> In the film, Coca-Cola was briefly seen being served at Dominic Greene's party. Sony held a competition, "Mission for a Million," enabling registered players to use their products to complete certain tasks. Each completed "mission" gives consumers a chance to win $1 million and a trip to a top secret location.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mission for a Million|publisher=[[Sony]]|url=http://www.sonymissionmillion.com/|accessdate=2008-10-04}}</ref>

====Merchandise====
[[File:CA1208cover-James Bond.jpg‎|thumb|right|The cover of ''Cigar Aficionado''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s special ''Quantum of Solace'' James Bond edition written by [[David Giammarco]].]]
[[Corgi International Limited]] made 5-inch action figures and gadgets (such as a voice-activated briefcase), as well as their traditional [[die-cast toy]] vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |title=New 007 Toys & Gadgets 2008 |work=[[MI6.co.uk]] |date=2008-02-13|url=http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/collecting_corgi_2008_toyfair3.php3 |accessdate=2008-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New Corgi Cars 2008 |work=[[MI6.co.uk]] |date=2008-02-03|url=http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/collecting_corgi_2008_toyfair2.php3 |accessdate=2008-02-27}}</ref> They also created 7-inch figures of characters from the previous films.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Corgi Action Figures|work=[[MI6.co.uk]] |date=2008-02-24|url=http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/collecting_corgi_2008_toyfair1.php3 |accessdate=2008-02-27}}</ref> [[Scalextric]] released four racing sets to coincide with the film.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scalextric 007 Racing Sets Unveiled |work=[[MI6.co.uk]] |date=2008-02-24|url=http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/collecting_scalextric_2008_toyfair.php3?t=&s= |accessdate=2008-02-27}}</ref> [[Activision]] released their first James Bond game, also titled ''[[Quantum of Solace (video game)|Quantum of Solace]]'', which is based on both ''Casino Royale'' and ''Quantum of Solace''. It is the first [[James Bond (games)|Bond game]] to feature Craig's likeness and the first [[History of video game consoles (seventh generation)|seventh generation console]] game in the series. [[Swatch]] designed a series of wrist watches, each of them inspired by a Bond villain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Swatch Launch 007 Villains Watches|work=[[MI6.co.uk]]|date=2008-09-09|url=http://www.mi6.co.uk/sections/articles/collecting_swatch_2008_launch.php3?t=&s=&id=02007|accessdate=2008-11-14}}</ref>

Though there was no [[novelization|novelisation]] despite its original storyline, [[Penguin Books]] published a compilation of Fleming's short stories entitled ''[[Quantum of Solace (short story collection)|Quantum of Solace: The Complete James Bond Short Stories]]'', with a UK release date of 29 May 2008<ref>[http://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/0141189622 Amazon.co.uk listing]. Retrieved 28 June 2008.</ref> and a North American release date of 26 August 2008.<ref>[http://www.amazon.com/dp/0143114581 Amazon.com listing], accessed 24 May 2008</ref> The book combines the contents of Fleming's two short story collections, ''[[For Your Eyes Only (short story collection)|For Your Eyes Only]]''—including the original "Quantum of Solace" short story—and ''[[Octopussy and The Living Daylights]]''.

The November/December 2008 issue of [[Cigar Aficionado]] was a special James Bond edition written by [[David Giammarco]], noted author of [[For Your Eyes Only: Behind the Scenes of the James Bond Films]], and featured an extensive 20-page feature on the making of ''Quantum of Solace'' from his exclusive interviews on location with Daniel Craig, Gemma Arterton, Olga Kurylenko, Mathieu Amalric, director Marc Forster, and producers Barbara Broccoli and Michael G. Wilson. This tribute issue of the upscale magazine also featured Giammarco's in-depth profile of 007 author Ian Fleming and the 46-year history of the James Bond films. The ''[[Cigar Aficionado]]'' James Bond special edition became the magazine's biggest-selling issue around the world.

===Reception===
====Box office====
Upon its opening in the UK, the film grossed £4.9 million ($8 million), breaking the record for the largest Friday opening (31 October 2008) in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|author=Archie Thomas|title='Solace' makes quantum leap in U.K.|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=2008-11-01|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117995122.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|accessdate=2008-11-01}}</ref> The film then broke the UK opening weekend record, taking £15.5 million ($25 million) in its first weekend, surpassing the previous record of £14.9 million held by ''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]''. It earned a further £14.2 million in France and Sweden &ndash; where it opened on the same day &ndash;. The weekend gross of the equivalent of $US10.6 million in France was a record for the series, surpassing what ''Casino Royale'' made in five days by 16%. The $US2.7 million gross in Sweden was the fourth-highest opening for a film there.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bond film smashes weekend records|work=[[BBC News Online]]|date=2008-11-03|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7705631.stm|accessdate=2008-11-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Dave McNary|title=James Bond finds overseas 'Solace'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=2008-11-02|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117995151.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|accessdate=2008-11-03}}</ref>

The following week, the film was playing in sixty countries. It grossed the equivalent of $US39.3 million in the UK, $US16.5 million in France and $US7.7 million in Germany on 7 November 2008.<ref>{{cite news|author=Pamela McClintock|title='Quantum' leap in overseas box office|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=2008-11-08|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117995539.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|accessdate=2008-11-09}}</ref> The film broke records in Switzerland, Finland, United Arab Emirates, Nigeria, Romania and Slovenia. Its Chinese and Indian openings were the second largest ever for foreign-language films.<ref>{{cite news|author=Dave McNary|title='Quantum' rules foreign box office|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=2008-11-09|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117995548.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|accessdate=2008-11-10}}</ref>

The film grossed [[USD|$]]27 million on its opening day in 3,451 theatres in [[Canada]] and the [[United States]], where it was the #1 film for the weekend, with $US67.5 million and $US19,568 average per theatre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?view=&yr=2008&wknd=46&p=.htm | title=Weekend Box Office Results from 11/14 - 11/16 | publisher=Box Office Mojo | accessdate=2008-11-14}}</ref> It was the highest-grossing opening weekend Bond film in the US,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=jamesbond.htm | title=James Bond Movies | publisher=Box Office Mojo | accessdate=2008-11-14}}</ref> and tied with ''[[The Incredibles]]'' for the biggest November opening outside of the ''[[Harry Potter (film series)|Harry Potter]]'' series. The film earned a B- from [[CinemaScore]]'s audience surveys.<ref>{{cite news|author=Joshua Rich|title='Quantum of Solace' Stirs up a Win|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=2008-11-16|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20240780,00.html|accessdate=2008-11-17}}</ref> From the 31 October British opening through to the November 14 US opening weekend, the film had grossed a total $US319,128,882 worldwide. As of 10 February 2010, it has grossed the equivalent of $US417,722,300 in countries other than Canada and the U.S.A., where it grossed $US168,368,427, to give a total of $US586,090,727.<ref name="BOM">{{cite web|title=Quantum of Solace (2008)|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=jamesbond22.htm|accessdate=2009-04-06}}</ref>

====Critical response====
Reviews for ''Quantum of Solace'' have been mixed. Of the 241 reviews listed on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], 63% are positive, with an average rating of 6.1/10. However, only 36% of selected notable reviewers gave it a positive write-up, with an average rating of 5.6/10.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Quantum of Solace''|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/|accessdate=2008-10-25}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] calculated a score of 58 out of 100 from 38 reviews, indicating a "mixed or average" response.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/quantumofsolace|title=Quantum of Solace|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref> Critics generally preferred ''Casino Royale'', but continued to praise Craig's depiction of Bond, and agree that the film is still an enjoyable addition to the series. The action sequences and pacing were praised, but criticism grew over the serious and gritty feel that the film carried over.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tom Butler|title=UK Tomatometer Preview: Quantum Of Solace - Is the New Bond Shaken or Stirred?|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|date=2008-10-31|url=http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/news/1777726/uk_tomatometer_preview_quantum_of_solace_is_the_new_bond_shaken_or_stirred|accessdate=2008-11-01}}</ref> 

[[Roger Moore]], the third actor to play Bond in the films, continued to feel Craig was a "damn good Bond but the film as a whole, there was a bit too much flash cutting [and] it was just like a commercial of the action. There didn't seem to be any geography and you were wondering what the hell was going on."<ref>{{cite news|title=Sir Roger Moore weighs in on `Quantum of Solace`|work=[[MI6.co.uk]]|date=2009-03-16|url=http://www.mi6.co.uk/news/index.php?itemid=7432&t=mi6&s=news|accessdate=2009-03-17}}</ref> 

[[Kim Newman]] of ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' gave it 4/5, remarking it was not "bigger and better than ''Casino Royale'', [which is] perhaps a smart move in that there's still a sense at the finish that Bond’s mission has barely begun." However, he expressed nostalgia for the more humorous Bond films.<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Kim Newman]]|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=134523|title=''Quantum of Solace'' (12A)|work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire Online]]|accessdate=2008-10-22}}</ref> ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' review noted that "[f]ollowing ''Casino Royale'' was never going to be easy, but the director Marc Forster has brought the brand’s successful relaunch crashing back to earth — with a yawn"; the screenplay "is at times incomprehensible" and the casting "is a mess." The review concludes that "Bond has been stripped of his iconic status. He no longer represents anything particularly British, or even modern. In place of glamour, we get a spurious grit; instead of style, we get [[product placement]]; in place of fantasy, we get a redundant and silly realism."<ref>{{cite news|author=[[Cosmo Landesman]]|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/film_reviews/article5001623.ece|title=Quantum of Solace - The Sunday Times review|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=2008-10-26|accessdate=2008-10-28 | location=London}}</ref> 

''The Guardian'' gave a more positive review, rating it as 3/5 stars,<!--more than the Sunday Times that is--> and was particularly fond of Craig's performance, saying he 
"made the part his own, every inch the coolly ruthless agent-killer, nursing a broken heart and coldly suppressed rage" and calling the film "a crash-bang Bond, high on action, low on quips, long on location glamour, short on product placement"; it concludes "''Quantum of Solace'' isn't as good as ''Casino Royale'': the smart elegance of Craig's Bond debut has been toned down in favour of conventional action. But the man himself powers this movie; he carries the film: it's an indefinably difficult task for an actor. Craig measures up."<ref>{{cite news|author=[[Peter Bradshaw]]|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2008/oct/18/jamesbond1|title=Quantum of Solace|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=2008-10-18|accessdate=2008-10-28 | location=London}}</ref>

''[[:en:Screen International|Screen Daily]]'' says "Notices will focus - rightly - on Craig's magnetism as the steely, sexy, murderous MI6 agent, but two other factors weigh in and freshen up proceedings: Forster's new technical team, led by cinematographer Roberto Schaefer and production designer Dennis Gassner. And the ongoing shift of M, as played by Judi Dench, to front and centre: the Bond girls fade into insignificance as she becomes his moral counterpoint and theirs is the only real relationship on screen." The review continues, "Bond is, as has been previously noted, practically the [[Martin Scorsese]] of the [[BAFTA]]s: 22 films later, with grosses probably close to the [[GDP]] of one of the small nations it depicts, it's still waiting for that [[Alexander Korda]] award. The best ''Casino Royale'' could achieve was a gong for sound. Will this be the year that changes its fortunes?"<ref>{{cite web|title=Fionnuala Halligan|title=Quantum of Solace|work=Screen Daily|date=2008-10-20|url=http://www.screendaily.com/ScreenDailyArticle.aspx?intStoryID=41477|accessdate=2008-11-01}}</ref>

[[Roger Ebert]] of ''[[The Chicago Sun-Times]]'', who praised the previous film, disliked ''Quantum of Solace''. He wrote that the plot was mediocre, characters weak and that Bond lacked his usual personality, despite his praise for Craig's interpretation of the role. Throughout his review, he emphasised that "James Bond is not an action hero," and also criticised the lack of a fantastical villainous lair and the Bond girls' names not being [[double entendres]].<ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081111/REVIEWS/811129989 Review] by Roger Ebert, November 12, 2008</ref>
Some writers criticised the choice of ''Quantum of Solace'' as a title. "Yes, it's a bad title," wrote Marni Weisz, the editor of ''Famous'', a [[Canada|Canadian]] film publication distributed in movie theatres in that country, in an editorial entitled "At least it's not ''[[Octopussy (film)|Octopussy]]''."<ref>Marni Weisz, "At least it's not Octopussy," ''Famous'', October 2008, p. 6</ref>

====Awards====
The film was nominated for Best Original Score, Best Original Song, Visual Effects, Film and Sound Editing at the 2008 [[Satellite Awards]], winning Best Song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressacademy.com/satawards/awards2008.shtml|title=2008 13th Annual SATELLITE Awards|publisher=[[International Press Academy]]|accessdate=2008-12-15}}</ref> It was nominated for Best Action Movie at the 2009 [[Critics' Choice Award]]s,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117997072.html?categoryId=13&cs=1|author=Dade Hayes|title=Critics Choice favors 'Milk,' 'Button'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=2008-12-09|accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref> and at the [[Empire Awards]], which is voted for by the public, it was shortlisted for Best Actor, Best Actress, Best Newcomer, Best Thriller and Best Soundtrack.<ref>{{cite news|title=Empire Awards nominate `Quantum of Solace` five times, vote now online|work=[[MI6.co.uk]]|date=2009-03-02|url=http://www.mi6.co.uk/news/index.php?itemid=7396&t=mi6&s=news|accessdate=2009-03-03}}</ref> It was nominated for the [[Saturn Award]] for Best Action/Adventure/Thriller Film, while Kurylenko and Dench were both nominated for the Best Supporting Actress award.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.saturnawards.org/nominations.html | title=Nominations for the 35th Annual Saturn Awards | publisher=[[Saturn Award|Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy & Horror Films]] | accessdate=2009-03-17}}</ref>  An editorial by ''[[The Times]]'' also listed the film's pre-titles sequence as the tenth greatest car chase in film history.<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Moran|title=The 20 greatest car chases in movie history|work=[[The Times]]|date=2008-11-20|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article5199765.ece?token=null&offset=0&page=1|accessdate=2008-12-03 | location=London}}</ref>

===Home Media===
''Quantum of Solace'' was released on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] by [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] in Australia, the UK and North America from 18 to 24 March 2009. At the DVD sales chart the film opened at #3, grossing $21,894,957 from 1.21m DVD units sold.<ref name="the-numbers1">{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2008/JB22-DVD.php |title=Quantum of Solace - DVD Sales |publisher=The Numbers |date= |accessdate=2009-11-01}}</ref> As of November 1, 2009 2,643,250 DVD units have been sold, generating $44,110,750 in sales revenue.<ref name="the-numbers1"/> These figures do not include Blu-ray sales or DVD rentals. They released the DVD in a standard one disc set and a deluxe two disc special edition. There are no audio commentaries or deleted scenes on these editions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Quantum of Solace Hits DVD & Blu-ray in March|work=ComingSoon.net|date=2009-01-13|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=51899|accessdate=2009-01-13}}</ref>

Like ''[[Casino Royale (2006 film)|Casino Royale]]'', no book adaptation of the movie was released despite having no relations with the short story except for its title. Instead, [[Penguin Books]] released ''[[Quantum of Solace (short story collection)|Quantum of Solace: The Complete James Bond Short Stories]]'' which is a compilation of both ''[[Octopussy and The Living Daylights]]'' and ''[[For Your Eyes Only (short story collection)|For Your Eyes Only]]'', both written by [[Ian Fleming]].

